# Automatically Called on Creation

The constructor is a special method that is automatically called when an object is created. It's used to initialize properties or perform setup tasks.

```php
class Car {
    public $color;

    public function __construct($color) {
        $this->color = $color;
        echo "A new car is created!";
    }
}

$myCar = new Car('red'); // passes 'red' to constructor
```

```php
<?php
class User {
    public $name;
    public $email;

    public function __construct($name, $email) {
        $this->name = $name;
        $this->email = $email;
    }

    public function introduce() {
        return "Hi, I'm $this->name, my email is $this->email";
    }
}

$user = new User('Alice', 'alice@example.com');
echo $user->introduce();
?>
```

# Cleanup

The destructor is called when an object is destroyed (e.g., at the end of script or when unset). It's useful for closing resources like file handles or database connections.

```php
class Logger {
    private $fileHandle;

    public function __construct($filename) {
        $this->fileHandle = fopen($filename, 'a');
    }

    public function log($message) {
        fwrite($this->fileHandle, date('Y-m-d H:i:s') . " - $message\n");
    }

    public function __destruct() {
        fclose($this->fileHandle);
    }
}
```
